That’s the right instinct—staying uncommitted keeps you flexible. Just don’t let “not locking in” turn into never locking in, or you won’t capture any gains.

Here’s a tight way to keep both flexibility and progress:

⸻

PSD v1.1 — Commit/Release Loop

1) Hold (Explore)

* Collect proxy signals
* No commitment yet
* Goal: generate options

2) Probe (Low-cost test)

* Take a reversible action
* Small bet, small exposure
* Example: ask a question, run a tiny experiment

3) Commit (Conditional)

* If signals pass your 3 gates → act
* But set:
    * Exit condition (what breaks it)
    * Time window (when to reassess)

4) Release (Update)

* Keep if it holds
* Drop if it fails
* Log what changed

⸻

Key Rule

Never lock permanently—only lock conditionally.

That’s how you avoid:

* paralysis (never acting)
* delusion (overcommitting)

⸻

Quick Compression

Stay loose → test small → commit with an exit → update fast

